=== 催化剂分离 ===
纳米级金属[[催化剂|催化剂]]是固定床和[[流化床|流化床]]{{efn|流化床是将一定量的固体颗粒物质（通常存在于容器中）置于适当条件下以使固体/流体混合物表现流体性质时发生的物理现象。}}化学气相沉积合成碳纳米管的重要成分。它们可以提高碳纳米管的生长效率，并控制其结构和手性。<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Size-selective growth of double-walled carbon nanotube forests from engineered iron catalysts |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nnano.2006.95 |journal=Nature Nanotechnology |issue=2 |doi=10.1038/nnano.2006.95 |year=2006 |volume=1 |pages=131–136 |bibcode=2006NatNa...1..131Y |pmid=18654165 |display-authors=etal |vauthors=Yamada T, Namai T, Hata K, Futaba DN, Mizuno K, Fan J}}</ref>在合成过程中，催化剂可以将碳[[前体|前体]]转化为管状碳结构，但也可以在外围形成一层碳涂层，与金属氧化物载体一起附着或结合到产品中。<ref>{{Cite journal |title=An updated review of synthesis parameters and growth mechanisms for carbon nanotubes in fluidized beds |url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/ie9019787 |journal=Industrial & Engineering Chemical Research |issue=11 |doi=10.1021/ie9019787 |year=2010 |volume=49 |pages=5323–38 |vauthors=MacKenzie KJ, Dunens OM, Harris AT |access-date=2020-11-29 |archive-date=2020-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200605121715/https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/ie9019787 |dead-url=no }}</ref>金属杂质的存在会产生许多应用上的问题，尤其是[[镍|镍]]、[[钴|钴]]或[[钇|钇]]之类的催化剂金属可能会引起毒理学问题。<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Jakubek LM, Marangoudakis S, Raingo J, Liu X, Lipscombe D, Hurt RH|title=The inhibition of neuronal calcium ion channels by trace levels of yttrium released from carbon nanotubes|url=https://archive.org/details/sim_biomaterials_2009-11_30_31/page/6351|journal=Biomaterials|volume=30|issue=31|pages=6351–6357|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2009.08.009|pmid=19698989|year=2009|last2=Marangoudakis|last3=Raingo|last4=Liu|last5=Lipscombe|last6=Hurt|pmc=2753181}}</ref>未封装的催化剂金属很容易通过酸洗去除，而封装的催化剂则需要进行氧化处理才能打开碳外壳。<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Purification of carbon nanotubes |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S000862230800448X?via%3Dihub |journal=Carbon |issue=15 |doi=10.1016/j.carbon.2008.09.009 |year=2008 |volume=46 |pages=2003–2025 |vauthors=Hou PX, Liu C, Cheng HM |access-date=2020-11-29 |archive-date=2017-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101111356/http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S000862230800448X?via%3Dihub |dead-url=no }}</ref>如何在保留碳纳米管结构的同时有效去除催化剂，尤其是封装的催化剂是一项挑战。<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Ebbesen TW, Ajayan PM, Hiura H, Tanigaki K|title=Purification of nanotubes|journal=Nature|volume=367|page=519|doi=10.1038/367519a0|year=1994|bibcode = 1994Natur.367..519E|issue=6463|last2=Ajayan|last3=Hiura|last4=Tanigaki}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Controlled multistep purification of single-walled carbon nanotubes |author=Xu Y-Q, Peng H, Hauge RH, Smalley RE |url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/nl048300s |last2=Peng |journal=Nano Letters |issue=1 |doi=10.1021/nl048300s |year=2005 |volume=5 |pages=163–168 |bibcode=2005NanoL...5..163X |pmid=15792432 |last3=Hauge |last4=Smalley |citeseerx=10.1.1.739.1034 |access-date=2020-11-29 |archive-date=2020-12-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201209150500/https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/nl048300s |dead-url=no }}</ref>一种打破碳质催化剂包封的新方法是快速热退火。<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Plasma-thermal purification and annealing of carbon nanotubes |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0008622312003648?via%3Dihub |journal=Carbon |issue=10 |doi=10.1016/j.carbon.2012.04.049 |year=2012 |volume=50 |pages=3934–3942 |display-authors=etal |vauthors=Meyer-Plath A, Orts-Gil G, Petrov S}}</ref>


=== 表征 ===
在合成、提纯完成后，表征是检测碳纳米管纯度与掺杂情况的最佳方法。透射电子显微镜，拉曼光谱，热重分析和近红外光谱是表征的常用仪器。<ref name="Nondestructive Approach">{{cite journal |author1=Jie Ma |coauthors=Jian Nong Wang |title=Purification of Single-Walled Carbon Nanotubes by a Highly Efficient and Nondestructive Approach |journal=chemistry of materials |date=2008-03-25 |volume=9 |issue=20 |pages=2895–2902 |doi=10.1021/cm8001699 |url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/cm8001699 |accessdate=2020-11-29 |publisher=ACS Publications |location=美国 |language=en |format=pdf |quote=Experimental results, based on transmission electron microscopy, Raman spectroscopy, thermogravimetric analysis, and near-infrared spectroscopy, show that catalytic particles and encapsulating graphitic shells can be removed. |archive-date=2020-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201210045648/https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/cm8001699 |dead-url=no }}</ref>

== 应用相关问题==

Many electronic applications of carbon nanotubes crucially rely on techniques of selectively producing either semiconducting or metallic CNTs, preferably of a certain chirality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Janas|first=Dawid|date=2018|title=Towards monochiral carbon nanotubes: a review of progress in the sorting of single-walled carbon nanotubes|journal=Materials Chemistry Frontiers|volume=2|issue=1|pages=36–63|doi=10.1039/C7QM00427C|issn=2052-1537}}</ref> Several methods of separating semiconducting and metallic CNTs are known, but most of them are not yet suitable for large-scale technological processes. The most efficient method relies on density-gradient ultracentrifugation, which separates surfactant-wrapped nanotubes by the minute difference in their density. This density difference often translates into difference in the nanotube diameter and (semi)conducting properties.<ref name=grad/> Another method of separation uses a sequence of freezing, thawing, and compression of SWNTs embedded in {{tsl|en|agarose||agarose}} gel. This process results in a solution containing 70% metallic SWNTs and leaves a gel containing 95% semiconducting SWNTs. The diluted solutions separated by this method show various colors.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Simple and Scalable Gel-Based Separation of Metallic and Semiconducting Carbon Nanotubes|journal=[[奈米通訊|Nano Letters]]|volume=9|pages=1497–1500|year=2009|doi=10.1021/nl8034866 |pmid=19243112 |issue=4 |last1=Tanaka |first1=Takeshi |last2=Jin |first2=Hehua |last3=Miyata |first3=Yasumitsu |last4=Fujii |first4=Shunjiro |last5=Suga |first5=Hiroshi |last6=Naitoh |first6=Yasuhisa |last7=Minari |first7=Takeo |last8=Miyadera |first8=Tetsuhiko |last9=Tsukagoshi |first9=Kazuhito|last10=Kataura|first10=Hiromichi|bibcode = 2009NanoL...9.1497T |display-authors=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=T.Tanaka|title=New, Simple Method for Separation of Metallic and Semiconducting Carbon Nanotubes|url=http://www.aist.go.jp/aist_e/latest_research/2009/20090406/20090406.html|access-date=2020-11-26|archive-date=2009-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629060536/http://www.aist.go.jp/aist_e/latest_research/2009/20090406/20090406.html|dead-url=yes}}</ref> The separated carbon nanotubes using this method have been applied to electrodes, e.g. electric double-layer capacitor.<ref name="yamada">{{Cite journal | last1 = Yamada | first1 = Y. | last2 = Tanaka | first2 = T. | last3 = Machida | first3 = K. | last4 = Suematsu | first4 = S. | last5 = Tamamitsu | first5 = K. | last6 = Kataura | first6 = H. | last7 = Hatori | first7 = H. | doi = 10.1016/j.carbon.2011.09.062 | title = Electrochemical behavior of metallic and semiconducting single-wall carbon nanotubes for electric double-layer capacitor | journal = Carbon | volume = 50 | issue = 3 | pages = 1422–1424 | year = 2012 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref> Moreover, SWNTs can be separated by the [[柱色谱法|column chromatography]] method. Yield is 95% in semiconductor type SWNT and 90% in metallic type SWNT.<ref>
{{cite journal |title=Continuous Separation of Metallic and Semiconducting Carbon Nanotubes Using Agarose Gel|journal=Applied Physics Express|volume=2|page=125002|year=2009|doi=10.1143/APEX.2.125002 |issue=12 |last1=Tanaka |first1=Takeshi |last2=Urabe |first2=Yasuko |last3=Nishide |first3=Daisuke |last4=Kataura |first4=Hiromichi|bibcode = 2009APExp...2l5002T }}</ref>

In addition to separation of semiconducting and metallic SWNTs, it is possible to sort SWNTs by length, diameter, and chirality. The highest resolution length sorting, with length variation of <10%, has thus far been achieved by size exclusion chromatography (SEC) of DNA-dispersed carbon nanotubes (DNA-SWNT).<ref>{{cite journal | title=High-Resolution Length Sorting and Purification of DNA-Wrapped Carbon Nanotubes by Size-Exclusion Chromatography|journal={{tsl|en|Anal. Chem.||Anal. Chem.}}|volume=77|pages=6225–6228|year=2005|doi=10.1021/ac0508954 |pmid=16194082 |issue=19 | last1=Huang | first1=Xueying | last2=McLean | first2=Robert S. | last3=Zheng | first3=Ming}}</ref> SWNT diameter separation has been achieved by density-gradient ultracentrifugation (DGU)<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mark C Hersam |title=Progress towards monodisperse single-walled carbon nanotubes|journal=Nature Nanotechnology|volume=3|pages=387–394|year=2008|doi=10.1038/nnano.2008.135 |pmid=18654561 |issue=7|bibcode = 2008NatNa...3..387H }}</ref> using surfactant-dispersed SWNTs and by ion-exchange chromatography (IEC) for DNA-SWNT.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Structure-Based Carbon Nanotube Sorting by Sequence-Dependent DNA Assembly|journal=Science|volume=302|pages=1545–1548|year=2003|doi=10.1126/science.1091911 |pmid=14645843 |issue=5650 | last1=Zheng | first1=M. | last2=Jagota | first2=A | last3=Strano | first3=MS | last4=Santos | first4=AP | last5=Barone | first5=P | last6=Chou | first6=SG | last7=Diner | first7=BA | last8=Dresselhaus | first8=MS | last9=McLean | first9=RS|last10=Onoa|first10=G. B.|last11=Samsonidze|first11=G. G.|last12=Semke|first12=E. D.|last13=Usrey|first13=M|last14=Walls|first14=D. J.|bibcode = 2003Sci...302.1545Z |display-authors=8}}</ref> Purification of individual chiralities has also been demonstrated with IEC of DNA-SWNT: specific short DNA oligomers can be used to isolate individual SWNT chiralities. Thus far, 12 chiralities have been isolated at purities ranging from 70% for (8,3) and (9,5) SWNTs to 90% for (6,5), (7,5) and (10,5)SWNTs.<ref>{{cite journal |title=DNA sequence motifs for structure-specific recognition and separation of carbon nanotubes|journal=Nature|volume=460|pages=250–253|year=2009|doi=10.1038/nature08116 |pmid=19587767 |issue=7252 |last1=Tu |first1=Xiaomin |last2=Manohar |first2=Suresh |last3=Jagota |first3=Anand |last4=Zheng |first4=Ming|bibcode = 2009Natur.460..250T }}</ref> Alternatively, carbon nanotubes have been successfully sorted by chirality using the [[双水相系统|aqueous two phase extraction]] method.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khripin|first=Constantine Y|last2=Fagan|first2=Jeffrey A.|last3=Zheng|first3=Ming|date=2013-05-08|title=Spontaneous Partition of Carbon Nanotubes in Polymer-Modified Aqueous Phases|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|volume=135|issue=18|pages=6822–6825|doi=10.1021/ja402762e|pmid=23611526|issn=0002-7863}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Han|last2=Gordeev|first2=Georgy|last3=Garrity|first3=Oisin|last4=Reich|first4=Stephanie|last5=Flavel|first5=Benjamin S.|date=2019-01-28|title=Separation of Small-Diameter Single-Walled Carbon Nanotubes in One to Three Steps with Aqueous Two-Phase Extraction|journal=ACS Nano|volume=13|issue=2|pages=2567–2578|doi=10.1021/acsnano.8b09579|pmid=30673278|issn=1936-0851}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Turek|first=Edyta|last2=Shiraki|first2=Tomohiro|last3=Shiraishi|first3=Tomonari|last4=Shiga|first4=Tamehito|last5=Fujigaya|first5=Tsuyohiko|last6=Janas|first6=Dawid|date=December 2019|title=Single-step isolation of carbon nanotubes with narrow-band light emission characteristics|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=9|issue=1|pages=535|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-37675-4|issn=2045-2322|pmc=6345979|pmid=30679809|bibcode=2019NatSR...9..535T}}</ref> There have been successful efforts to integrate these purified nanotubes into devices, e. g. FETs.<ref>{{cite journal| title=Optical characterizations and electronic devices of nearly pure (10,5) single-walled carbon nanotubes|journal=[[美国化学会志|J Am Chem Soc]]|volume=131|pages=2454–2455|year=2009|doi=10.1021/ja8096674 |pmid=19193007 |issue=7| last1=Zhang| first1=Li| last2=Tu| first2=Xiaomin| last3=Welsher| first3=Kevin| last4=Wang| first4=Xinran| last5=Zheng| first5=Ming| last6=Dai| first6=Hongjie|arxiv=0902.0010|bibcode=2009arXiv0902.0010Z}}</ref>

An alternative to separation is development of a selective growth of semiconducting or metallic CNTs. Recently, a new CVD recipe that involves a combination of ethanol and methanol gases and quartz substrates resulting in horizontally aligned arrays of 95–98% semiconducting nanotubes was announced.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/nl803496s|title=Selective Growth of Well-Aligned Semiconducting Single-Walled Carbon Nanotubes|year=2009| journal=Nano Letters|volume=9|pages=800–5|pmid=19159186|issue=2|last1=Ding|first1=Lei|last2=Tselev|first2=Alexander|last3=Wang|first3=Jinyong|last4=Yuan|first4=Dongning|last5=Chu|first5=Haibin|last6=McNicholas|first6=Thomas P.|last7=Li|first7=Yan|last8=Liu|first8=Jie|bibcode = 2009NanoL...9..800D }}</ref>

Nanotubes are usually grown on nanoparticles of magnetic metal (Fe, Co), which facilitates production of electronic ([[自旋電子學|spintronic]]) devices. In particular, control of current through a field-effect transistor by magnetic field has been demonstrated in such a single-tube nanostructure.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mohd Ambri |last=Mohamed|title=Fabrication of spintronics device by direct synthesis of single-walled carbon nanotubes from ferromagnetic electrodes|journal=Sci. Technol. Adv. Mater.|volume=9|issue=2|year=2008|page=025019|doi=10.1088/1468-6996/9/2/025019|pmid=27877994 |pmc=5099751 |first2=Nobuhito |last2=Inami |first3=Eiji |last3=Shikoh |first4=Yoshiyuki |last4=Yamamoto |first5=Hidenobu |last5=Hori |first6=Akihiko |last6=Fujiwara|bibcode = 2008STAdM...9b5019A }}</ref>

